Data Workflows II - Tidyverse - KEY

+

\(+\)

\(=\)

Impetus

This homework focuses on how we can use tidyverse routines to become more effective in our pre-treatment of data. As a removner, the operative verbs we use in data preparation include:

  • Select
  • Filter
  • Mutating
  • Arranging
  • Grouping
  • Summarizing

These can be combined in various ways to gain inferences from the raw data.

## The Data

The Questions

Provide your answers as text (e.g., using complete sentences, etc.) and include visual output in tabular or graphical form to support your assertions. The key point here is that you need to develop an evidence-based narrative to address these questions.

  1. On average, is there more rain on Mondays, at daytime, or at night?
Mean and standard deviation of rain on Mondays at the Rice Center.
Period Rain SD
Day 0.0081 0.0366
Night 0.0012 0.0124
  1. What is the overall relationship between salinity and pH? Does this pattern hold when considering each month individually?

So overall, there seems to be a slightly positive relationship at levels. A non-parametric correlation concurs.

cor.test( rice$Salinity_ppt, rice$PH, method = "spearman")

Cannot compute exact p-value with ties

    Spearman's rank correlation rho

data:  rice$Salinity_ppt and rice$PH
S = 7.1134e+10, p-value < 2.2e-16
alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
sample estimates:
      rho 
0.2253529
